he governing logics of the global health economy have transformed the relations—between and within bodies, medical technologies, friends, kin, and organizations—that care requires and how such transformations pose new challenges for ethnographic analysis and critique.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMedical carezMozambique. 0aMedicinexResearchzMozambique. 0aNon-governmental organizationszMozambique. 0aPublic healthzMozambiquexInternational cooperation. 0aPublic healthzMozambique. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106963320 cprintz978082237010940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822372196423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822372196/original  a978-3-11-069633-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles